# KServe Raw Mode Deployment

This standalone directory contains all the manifests required to install **KServe configured for Raw Deployment Mode**, ensuring that InferenceServices deploy as standard Kubernetes Deployments/Services (no Knative or Istio required).

## Prerequisite: cert-manager

KServe webhooks require [cert-manager](https://cert-manager.io/) for TLS certificate provisioning. It is **not bundled** with this package — install it on the cluster yourself before running the installer.

```bash
# Pinned stable release — check https://github.com/cert-manager/cert-manager/releases for latest
kubectl apply -f https://github.com/cert-manager/cert-manager/releases/download/v1.17.2/cert-manager.yaml
kubectl wait --for=condition=Ready pods --all -n cert-manager --timeout=180s
```

Verify:
```bash
kubectl get crds | grep cert-manager.io
```

The installer (`install.sh`) checks for cert-manager and exits with a clear error if it is missing.

## Directory Structure

> Numbering starts at `02` because slot `01` is reserved for cert-manager, which is now a cluster prerequisite (see above) rather than a bundled component.

1. `02-kserve-crds`: KServe Custom Resource Definitions.
2. `03-kserve-rbac`: KServe ClusterRoles and authentication bindings.
3. `04-kserve-core`: The KServe Controller Manager (Patched with `"defaultDeploymentMode": "RawDeployment"` and explicitly appends the `selfsigned-issuer` so webhooks can establish TLS).
4. `05-kserve-runtimes`: Default Predictor Runtimes (Scikit-Learn, PyTorch, Triton, HuggingFace).
5. `06-sample-model`: A sample `sklearn-iris` model and its test payload.
6. `install.sh`: An automated deployment script handling the webhook sleep sequences.

## Installation
Ensure you are connected to a healthy Kubernetes cluster and that **cert-manager is installed** (see above).

### Fast Installation
Simply execute the installer script from this directory:
```bash
./install.sh
```

### Manual Installation
If applying manually, you must follow this exact order and wait for the pods in the previous step to become `Ready` before proceeding:
```bash
kubectl apply --server-side -f 02-kserve-crds/kserve-crds.yaml
kubectl apply -f 03-kserve-rbac/kserve-rbac.yaml
kubectl apply --server-side -f 04-kserve-core/kserve-core.yaml

# WAIT 15+ SECONDS for Webhooks to register their IPs in Kubernetes!
kubectl apply --server-side -f 05-kserve-runtimes/kserve-cluster-resources.yaml
```

## Validation
To prove the cluster is working, deploy the sample model:
```bash
kubectl apply -f 06-sample-model/sklearn-iris.yaml
```
Once `Ready`, test it directly without ingress routing:
```bash
kubectl port-forward svc/sklearn-iris-predictor 8080:80 &
curl -s -X POST -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d @06-sample-model/iris-input.json http://localhost:8080/v1/models/sklearn-iris:predict
```
